My Apple Pencil just got a comfy glow-up thanks to the fab new Pencil Grips my friends at @Paperlike sent me last week. 🤩⁣
⁣
Creating the artwork for this Reel was the perfect way to test them out. I shot a photo of my Apple Pencil with the grips on a chalkboard-like background. Then I edited and brought the photo into Procreate to add the lettering. ⁣
⁣
I started using the Precision Grip, but my hand started cramping around the two-hour mark, so I switched to the Comfort Grip. The cheap grip I had before slipped around, which was super annoying, so my favorite thing about these is how snugly they fit my Apple Pencil. ⁣
⁣
DM me if you’d like a link to check these out!  ⁣
⁣

I spent hours yesterday making a list of ideas to letter and illustrate based on some of my favorite songs from that time. ⁣

I’m kicking it off with this Garbage song. I first lettered these lyrics four years ago, and I know you all love a good “now and then” post. Swipe to see my version of this artwork in 2019 vs. today.⁣
⁣
✏️ The serif lettering style in this artwork is one of ten I created for my upcoming book with @better_day_books called Halcyon.⁣
✏️ You can get a sneak peek at the full Halcyon alphabet if you swipe to the process video.⁣
✏️ Time: I spent just shy of five hours drawing this one.⁣
✏️ I mainly used brushes and stamps from my Modern Folk Art and Artsy Aesthetic Procreate Brush Kits for this piece.⁣

Spending a Day Date on the golf course with the Hubby in celebration of our sixteenth wedding anniversary tomorrow! ⛳️🩷 ⁣
⁣
Learning something new can be intimidating, whether hand-lettering, golf or any other skill. ⁣
⁣
My husband had been trying to get me to try golfing with him for years, but I was perfectly content to stay home reading a book while he golfed with the guys. I was also scared I would suck at it.⁣
⁣
About six months or so ago, he finally convinced me to try. I can’t even remember why I finally said yes, but I remember jokingly asking him: “I don’t nag you enough at home? You want me with you on the golf course?!” 😂⁣
⁣
I was so nervous the first few times at the driving range. I was even more nervous the first time we hit the golf course. ⁣
⁣
During one of my Peloton workouts not long ago, instructor Jess Sims said:⁣
⁣
“𝐁𝐞𝐢𝐧𝐠 𝐫𝐞𝐚𝐝𝐲 𝐢𝐬 𝐚 𝐝𝐞𝐜𝐢𝐬𝐢𝐨𝐧, 𝐧𝐨𝐭 𝐚 𝐟𝐞𝐞𝐥𝐢𝐧𝐠.”⁣
⁣
I never imagined I’d enjoy golfing as much as I do. I’d be missing out on something active that we enjoy doing together if I hadn’t hit the course that first time, despite not feeling ready.⁣
⁣
Now, we go to the driving range twice a week. I’ve played 9 holes twice and 18 holes three times (as of tomorrow). I’m growing my collection of cute golf attire and pink golf balls. ⁣
⁣
Sometimes I drive the ball straight on the fairway; other times, it lands in the water. 🤷‍♀️ ⁣
⁣
Most of the time though, I surprise myself and hit  the ball well for a newbie!⁣
⁣
I’m still learning the (many) rules, the terminology, and why golf is such a love/hate kind of game…but more than anything, I’m having SO. MUCH. FUN.⁣
⁣
Anyhow, the moral of this long-winded story is to try something new! You might just surprise yourself too. ⁣
⁣

The first of September always feels like the unofficial start of Autumn. ⁣
⁣
While the weather still hangs onto Summer, I’m all about Fall inside. Pumpkins are already strewn about my house and I’m pulling all my long-sleeved thumb-hole sweaters out of storage.⁣
⁣
I’ve got the most delicious-smelling Pistachio Biscotti candle lit in my office while I work on a lettering project this morning, and I’m dreaming about my first Oat Milk PSL of the season.⁣

My 8th grader is studying Edgar Allan Poe in class this week, and we were talking about this last night…so I gave it a little update to re-share with you.⁣
⁣
I originally shared this artwork and folklore after a Charleston ghost tour a we took a few years ago. ⁣
⁣
From Nov. 1827 to Dec. 1828, Poe was stationed at Fort Moultrie, and Charleston celebrates his connection to the city in a few fun ways.⁣⁣
⁣⁣
There’s the fantastic @poestavern restaurant and the Edgar Allen Poe library on Sullivan’s Island. ⁣
⁣
If you go on a Ghost Tour and stop at the Unitarian Church, you’ll likely hear the story about the origins of his famous poem, Annabel Lee. ⁣⁣
⁣⁣
Most scholars say that the poem is about Poe’s later wife. ⁣
⁣
But many Charlestonians say it’s about his forbidden love with a very young, wealthy local girl he met while stationed there. She was just 14 at the time. ⁣⁣
⁣⁣
It’s a long story you can Google and read, but the TLDR is that Annabel’s father disapproved of her relationship with the soldier. ⁣
⁣
He kept Annabel locked in her room to keep her away from him. She died while Poe was away on duty, and her father had her grave at the family plot dug to a depth of 6 feet. He had all the other graves in the family plot dug to 3 feet. ⁣
⁣
This was shallow enough so as not to disturb the graves but deep enough to make them all look freshly dug. ⁣⁣
⁣
And all were unmarked.⁣
⁣⁣
So when the sailor arrived back in Charleston, he went to the cemetery to visit her. He continued to do so every day and sit for hours. ⁣
⁣
Poe sat by the family plot in the Unitarian Cemetery to grieve her death, never knowing exactly which grave was Annabel’s.⁣⁣
⁣⁣
Rumor has it Annabel’s ghost still roams the cemetery of the Unitarian Church looking for her long-lost love, Poe.⁣⁣
⁣

Oh what fun it is to feel that elusive creative spark after a few months of feeling unmotivated and unsure of what comes next as a freelance artist. 💖✏️⁣
⁣
The ever-changing Internet and algorithms make small businesses need to constantly reassess and pivot. ⁣
⁣
Social media can feel especially draining for introverts such as myself.⁣
⁣
I’m not complaining. Truly. I’m mostly an “it what it is” kind of person who looks at the bright side.⁣
⁣
And I do love a good challenge. ⁣
⁣
But my “only human” side was often just too tired to figure out what comes next business-wise.⁣
⁣
From the outside, it might look like I did a lot this year. A book cover for another author, a published book of my own, new Procreate brushes, classes, and monthly newsletters. ⁣
⁣
Some of the work I’m most proud of came during this slump. ⁣
⁣
And yet…⁣
⁣
The truth is that I’ve been doing the bare minimum to stay afloat the past year or so. ⁣
⁣
I mostly buried myself in workouts and books…my favorite forms of escapism.⁣
⁣
The creative life ebbs and flows. Fake it ‘til you make it and all that.⁣
⁣
Social Media makes it seem like everyone else has it figured out, but we’re all just figuring it out as we go!⁣
⁣
All that to say, I’m feeling the creative vibes again and super excited about what I have planned for 2024. ⁣
⁣
Since this post is already too long, I’ll share more soon, but as I take a break for the Holidays, I wanted to leave you with a few things:⁣
⁣
✏️ 2024 will be my year to be Creatively Productive. I’ll be working on a Passion Project all year focused on book cover designs because that’s the work I’d most like to do more of. Some cover designs will be just for fun (like this one), and some will be real (🤞🏻).⁣
✏️ I created an 8-page Creatively Productive Planner + Guide you can download in my January newsletter. It will help you plan your own Passion Project for the year. ⁣
✏️ Every newsletter of 2024 will have a Creativity Tool Kit to keep the inspiration flowing all year!⁣
